references:
The parameter ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon is referred to as the privacy budget.
It quantifies the privacy leakage of a data release, with smaller ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon providing more protection.
Achieving DP with small to reasonable values of ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon can however require significant noise to be added to a machine learning model, decreasing its utility.
Efficiently achieving DP guarantees for ML models, including synthetic data generation models, is an active area of research. In this paper, we used the DP generator PrivBayes from the work of Zhang et al. [42]. We refer the reader to Sec. 1 for details.

Table 1 shows the parameters we use for the attack. We use a given dataset ΩΩ\Omega (e.g. Adult) to select our most at-risk records as the target records.

references: Figure 1 show that our vulnerable record identification method consistently outperforms both the random baseline and the two ad-hoc techniques previously used in the literature. The median risk of records identified by our method is indeed consistently higher than all other methods, up to 18.6 p.p. higher on the UK Census dataset using BayNet. On average, the AUC of the records we identified are 7.2 p.p. higher than the AUC of the records selected by other methods (Table 2). Importantly, our method also consistently manages to identify records that are more or equivalently at-risk compared to other methods.
